  "title": [
    {
      "type": "Text",
      "value": {
        "string": "Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
      }
    }
  ],
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "Heading",
      "level": 6,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "Key words and phrases:"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "multi-sector equilibrium, transition risk, carbon price, endogenous default, mean-field games"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Heading",
      "label": "1.",
      "level": 1,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "Introduction"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "A large-scale shift toward low-carbon technologies is essential to limit global warming and mitigate the most severe impacts of climate change. As governments implement policies to reduce emissions and consumer sentiment drives demand shocks, green firms are expected to gain market share, while brown firms—those unable to decarbonize—may face revenue losses, asset stranding, and even default. These transition risks can propagate through the real economy and the financial system, and must therefore be closely monitored by banks and supervisory authorities "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "CitationGroup",
          "items": [
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib11",
              "citationMode": "Parenthetical",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Basel Committee on Banking Supervision, 2021"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib12",
              "citationMode": "Parenthetical",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Basel Committee on Banking\nSupervision, 2022"
                  }
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "The prevailing methodology for assessing transition risks relies on climate stress testing "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Citation",
          "target": "bib.bib2",
          "citationMode": "Parenthetical",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Acharya et al., 2023"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ". A climate stress test evaluates the potential losses of financial institutions under specific transition scenarios using a combination of economic, financial, and physical models. The typical approach begins with an integrated assessment model that translates carbon price or demand shocks into a global macroeconomic trajectory and ends with a default model projecting firm-level distress "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Citation",
          "target": "bib.bib5",
          "citationMode": "Parenthetical",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "ACPR, 2020"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ". While pragmatic, this multi-model setup suffers from important limitations: inconsistencies across models, a lack of two-way feedback between macro and micro levels, and limited treatment of uncertainty."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "In this paper, we propose an alternative, integrated modeling framework to assess the impact of macroeconomic shocks—particularly carbon pricing—on transition risks and firm defaults. Our approach is based on the theory of mean-field games (MFGs), which provides the mathematical tractability needed to jointly capture endogenous default decisions under idiosyncratic shocks and realistic inter-sectoral input-output linkages within a unified model."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "We develop a multi-sector equilibrium model of the productive economy aimed at studying how carbon price shocks propagate through the value chain. Each sector comprises a continuum of firms producing a homogeneous good. Production requires inputs from other sectors, labor, and carbon emissions, and is described by a sector-specific production function. Sectors face endogenous demand from other sectors and exogenous consumer demand, and prices are determined endogenously via market clearing. Firms choose an optimal allocation of inputs—including labor, emissions, and goods from other sectors—to maximize profits. While production technologies are identical within each sector, firms are subject to idiosyncratic labor costs and interact through sectoral prices both within and across sectors."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "Firms also choose their optimal default timing to maximize shareholder value, resulting in exits at uncertain future dates. Since carbon emissions are essential to production, carbon price shocks raise marginal costs and may trigger firm default. A cascade of defaults in a carbon-sensitive sector can drive up the price of its output, thereby increasing costs in downstream sectors and amplifying default risk along the value chain."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "We model the economy as a coupled system of optimal stopping mean-field games—one for each sector. Following "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Citation",
          "target": "bib.bib23",
          "citationMode": "Narrative",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Bouveret et al. (2020)"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": " and "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Citation",
          "target": "bib.bib31",
          "citationMode": "Narrative",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Dumitrescu et al. (2021)"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ", we solve this system using a linear programming formulation, which characterizes Nash equilibria in terms of population measure flows. We prove the existence of a linear programming Nash equilibrium and establish uniqueness of the associated price system. To this end, we introduce an auxiliary Minimax problem and show that any saddle point corresponds to a MFG Nash equilibrium. This formulation enables us to prove existence via the existence of saddle points. The Minimax problem admits a natural interpretation as a social planner problem, in which the planner controls the distribution of agents and selects the price system to maximize aggregate surplus."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "Finally, we provide numerical illustrations using CES production functions and Cox – Ingersoll – Ross (CIR) processes for labor cost dynamics. We explore two scenarios: one with a single sector exposed to carbon price shocks, and another with three interconnected sectors (brown, green, and manufacturing) linked through a specified input–output network. Our simulations show that in the directly affected sector, capacity declines significantly in response to carbon pricing. Moreover, the shock propagates through the value chain, generating spillover effects. However, even large shocks rarely lead to abrupt waves of default, as firms optimally anticipate the rise in emission costs and, after an initial clearing, exit the market gradually."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "These findings support the view that an early-announced and stable policy framework facilitates smoother asset value adjustments and mitigates systemic risk."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Section",
      "sectionType": "Main",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Heading",
          "label": "1.1.",
          "level": 2,
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Structure of the paper"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "The remainder of the paper is organized as follows. The rest of this introduction reviews the relevant literature. Section "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Link",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "2"
                  }
                }
              ],
              "target": "S2",
              "title": "2. Firm-level profit maximization with carbon pricing ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " introduces the profit maximization problem of a single firm in a static setting. We prove the existence of profit-maximizing input configurations and provide explicit solutions in the case of CES production functions. Section "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Link",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "3"
                  }
                }
              ],
              "target": "S3",
              "title": "3. Price formation and competitive equilibrium in the static setting ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " extends the analysis to a multi-sector economy with a static price formation mechanism. We study the interaction between prices and input choices from a competitive equilibrium perspective and prove the existence of a competitive (Nash) equilibrium. Section "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Link",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "4"
                  }
                }
              ],
              "target": "S4",
              "title": "4. Mean-field game approach to a dynamic market model with defaults ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " develops a dynamic market model, where each sector is represented by a mean-field firm optimizing both production and default timing. Using the linear programming approach introduced in "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib23",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Bouveret et al. (2020)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib31",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Dumitrescu et al. (2021)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", we reformulate the optimal stopping problem as a linear program. We then establish the existence of a mean-field game Nash equilibrium and prove the uniqueness of the associated price system. Section "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Link",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "5"
                  }
                }
              ],
              "target": "S5",
              "title": "5. Numerical illustration ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " presents numerical illustrations, and Section "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Link",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "6"
                  }
                }
              ],
              "target": "S6",
              "title": "6. Conclusions ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " concludes."
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Section",
      "sectionType": "Main",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Heading",
          "label": "1.2.",
          "level": 2,
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Related literature"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "We briefly review the literature relevant to our work. Comprehensive overviews of the financial implications of climate change are provided by "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib24",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Campiglio et al. (2018)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib41",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Krueger et al. (2020)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ". The former emphasizes the role of central banks and financial regulators in facilitating the low-carbon transition, particularly through carbon pricing. The latter focuses on institutional investors and the influence of climate risks — especially regulatory risks — on portfolio decisions."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "This focus on risk has spurred stress-testing methodologies to assess financial vulnerabilities from regulatory shocks. "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib14",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Battiston et al. (2017)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " propose a network-based approach to capture financial interdependencies, while "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib21",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Bouchet and Le Guenedal (2020)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " use a bottom-up framework to evaluate corporate credit risk under carbon pricing scenarios. Several studies build on the Merton model "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib51",
              "citationMode": "Parenthetical",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Merton, 1974"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", including "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib25",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Capasso et al. (2020)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib54",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Reinders et al. (2023)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", who empirically show that firms with higher carbon footprints face higher perceived default risk, reinforcing the need to incorporate carbon exposure into credit risk assessments."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Further structural models include "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib60",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Wang et al. (2024)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib46",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Löschenbrand et al. (2024)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ". The former uses China’s accession to the Paris Agreement as an exogenous shock, finding that rising carbon risk can reduce defaults among high-emission firms — a possible regulatory gain. The latter combines financial and emissions data for over 2.5 million borrowers across major European banks. Their stress tests suggest that while high carbon prices pressure certain firms, systemic default risk in the Euro area remains limited."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Building on an earlier work by "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib7",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Agliardi and Agliardi (2021)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib43",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Le Guenedal and Tankov (2025)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " introduce an endogenous default model with partial information to price defaultable bonds under transition risk, whose severity depends on a latent scenario gradually revealed through the dynamics of the carbon price."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "A separate strand of literature studies the diffusion of carbon pricing across sectors using Input-Output (I-O) and equilibrium models. I-O analysis, rooted in Leontief’s work, models intersectoral dependencies "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib19",
              "citationMode": "Parenthetical",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Blair and Miller, 2009"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ". "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib6",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Adenot et al. (2022)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " apply this framework to the global economy using WIOD data under different carbon price scenarios. Related studies on Chile include "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib48",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Mardones and Muñoz (2018)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib47",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Mardones and Mena (2020)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Despite their tractability, I-O models assume fixed input proportions and do not model price responses. Equilibrium models address these limitations by allowing input substitution and price formation, typically under perfect competition."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Partial and general equilibrium models have been widely used to analyze carbon pricing. "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib53",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Neuhoff and Ritz (2019)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " adopt a partial equilibrium approach to study carbon pass-through within an industry. "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib36",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Frankovic (2024)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " uses a multisector, multiregional computable general equilibrium (CGE) model to evaluate spillover effects of global carbon pricing on Germany and Europe (see also "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib61",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Wei and Aaheim (2023)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ")."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "To incorporate time dynamics and uncertainty, these models evolve into dynamic stochastic general equilibrium (DSGE) frameworks, enabling richer firm behavior such as entry and exit. "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib52",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Miao (2005)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " develops a single-sector DSGE model with firm-level technology shocks, anticipating ideas later formalized in mean-field games (MFGs) by "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib42",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Lasry and Lions (2007)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "In the context of transition risk, "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib22",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Bouveret et al. (2023)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " build a DSGE model incorporating GHG emission costs in both production and consumption, linking carbon costs to credit portfolios. Similarly, "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib50",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Matsumura et al. (2024)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " model Japan’s economy using a DSGE framework with I-O structure and investment networks."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "DSGE models also offer normative insights. "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib38",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Golosov et al. (2014)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " derive a closed-form optimal carbon tax by solving a social planner’s problem with climate externalities, later extended by "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib58",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "van der Ploeg and Rezai (2021)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " to include global warming’s impact on utility and productivity growth."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "While powerful, DSGE models become intractable with many heterogeneous agents. Mean-field game theory, introduced by "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib42",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Lasry and Lions (2007)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", overcomes this curse of dimensionality by shifting the focus from individual agents to the “mean field”, which represents the aggregate behaviour of the population. MFGs arise as the asymptotic limit of stochastic differential games with many symmetric agents. Each agent controls a state variable influenced by idiosyncratic noise and the population distribution. In the limit, this leads to a coupled system of PDEs: a Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman (HJB) equation for the value function and a Fokker-Planck (FP) equation for the distribution dynamics. For a comprehensive discussion, see "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib27",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Carmona and Delarue (2018a)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib28",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Carmona and Delarue (2018b)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "While early MFG studies focused on solving this PDE system, an alternative formulation by "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib26",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Carmona and Delarue (2015)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " characterizes equilibria using forward-backward stochastic differential equations (FBSDEs)."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Extensions to MFGs include common noise, major players, singular controls, and optimal stopping. The latter is particularly relevant for entry-exit problems, though solving the HJB-FP system becomes difficult due to the free boundary. To overcome this, "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib23",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Bouveret et al. (2020)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib31",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Dumitrescu et al. (2021)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib32",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Dumitrescu et al. (2023)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " propose a novel reformulation of the optimal stopping problem as a linear program, where optimization is performed over population measure flows subject to a linear constraint imposed by the FP equation."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Mean-field games have found wide application in economics. For instance, "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib4",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Achdou et al. (2022)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " extend the Aiyagari–Bewley–Huggett model of income and wealth distribution to continuous time, using mean-field game theory to handle agent heterogeneity. In a related context, "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib3",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Achdou et al. (2023)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " model an economy composed of competing firms subject to idiosyncratic capital dynamics, focusing on stationary equilibria for the consumption problem under capital constraints. Further relevant applications of MFG theory in economics can be found in "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib9",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Alvarez et al. (2023)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib45",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Liang and Zhang (2024)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Applications of MFG modeling to climate and energy topics—including electricity markets and green transitions—have gained increasing attention. Notable contributions include "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "CitationGroup",
              "items": [
                {
                  "type": "Citation",
                  "target": "bib.bib39",
                  "citationMode": "Narrative",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": "Guéant et al. (, 2010"
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "Citation",
                  "target": "bib.bib35",
                  "citationMode": "Narrative",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": "), Escribe et al. (, 2024"
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "Citation",
                  "target": "bib.bib8",
                  "citationMode": "Narrative",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": "), Aïd et al. (, 2021"
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "Citation",
                  "target": "bib.bib13",
                  "citationMode": "Narrative",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": "), Bassiére et al. (, 2024"
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ". The latter two, in particular, address entry–exit problems in electricity markets involving conventional and renewable producers, employing a linear programming approach to characterize the MFG Nash equilibria. Their existence and uniqueness results rely on fixed-point arguments. In contrast, the present work also adopts the linear programming formulation but establishes the existence of equilibria via a Minimax approach."
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Heading",
      "label": "2.",
      "level": 1,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "Firm-level profit maximization with carbon pricing"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "In this section, we formulate and solve the profit maximization problem for a single firm operating in a fixed sector "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "MathInline",
          "code": {
            "string": "i\\in\\{1,\\dots,N\\}"
          },
          "mathLanguage": "latex",
          "mathml": "redacted"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": " in interaction with the other sectors. The production process is modeled by a function that combines inputs from all sectors, carbon emissions considered as input in the production process, and a local input such as capital or labor. The firm operates in a competitive market, optimizing its input decisions to maximize profits while treating prices as given. Under general assumptions on the production function and cost structure, we establish the existence of an optimal input choice. In the special case of a constant elasticity of substitution (CES) production function, we derive closed-form solutions for the firm’s optimal input allocation and output level. Proofs are presented in Appendix "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Link",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "A"
              }
            }
          ],
          "target": "A1",
          "title": "Appendix A Proofs of results from Section 2 ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Section",
      "sectionType": "Main",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Heading",
          "label": "2.1.",
          "level": 2,
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Production functions"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Let "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "q_{ij}"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " denote the quantity of good "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "j"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " used by the firm in its production process. We define "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "\\mathbf{q}_{i}\\coloneqq(q_{ij})_{j=1,\\dots,N}"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " as the vector of input quantities sourced by the firm from all sectors, including its own sector "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "i"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "In addition to sectoral inputs, we introduce two specific production inputs: "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "E_{i}"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", referred to as "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Emphasis",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "emissions"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", representing greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions resulting from the production process; and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "L_{i}"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", referred to as "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Emphasis",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "labor"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", encompassing both workforce and productive capital (e.g., machinery) employed in production."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "By treating emissions as an input — or “quasi-input” — to production, we follow the approach adopted in the environmental economics literature, notably in "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib33",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Ebert and Welsch (2007)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib29",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Considine and Larson (2006)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ". This formulation allows firms to substitute carbon-intensive technologies with labor - or capital - intensive alternatives, or with technologies relying on inputs from other sectors, in order to mitigate emission-related costs."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "The production function "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "F_{i}:\\mathbb{R}^{N+2}_{\\geq 0}\\to\\mathbb{R}_{\\geq 0}"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " maps the input quantities to the gross total output of the firm, which is given by"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "MathBlock",
          "code": {
            "string": "F_{i}(\\mathbf{q}_{i},E_{i},L_{i}),\\quad i=1,\\dots,N."
          },
          "mathLanguage": "latex",
          "mathml": "redacted"
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "To simplify notation, we denote the full vector of inputs as "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "\\mathbf{x}\\coloneqq(\\mathbf{q},E,L)\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N+2}_{\\geq 0}"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ". We assume that the production function satisfies the following standard conditions."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Claim",
          "claimType": "Theorem",
          "label": "2.1",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "The production function "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "F_{i}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " is increasing in each argument, upper semi-continuous, and concave. Additionally, "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "F_{i}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " satisfies one of the following alternative conditions:"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "List",
              "items": [
                {
                  "type": "ListItem",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "type": "Paragraph",
                      "content": []
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "Paragraph",
                      "content": [
                        {
                          "type": "MathInline",
                          "code": {
                            "string": "F_{i}(\\mathbf{x})=o(\\lVert\\mathbf{x}\\rVert)"
                          },
                          "mathLanguage": "latex",
                          "mathml": "redacted"
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "Text",
                          "value": {
                            "string": " as "
                          }
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "MathInline",
                          "code": {
                            "string": "\\lVert\\mathbf{x}\\rVert\\to\\infty"
                          },
                          "mathLanguage": "latex",
                          "mathml": "redacted"
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "Text",
                          "value": {
                            "string": "."
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "ListItem",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "type": "Paragraph",
                      "content": []
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "Paragraph",
                      "content": [
                        {
                          "type": "MathInline",
                          "code": {
                            "string": "F_{i}"
                          },
                          "mathLanguage": "latex",
                          "mathml": "redacted"
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "Text",
                          "value": {
                            "string": " is homogeneous of degree one, meaning that"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "MathBlock",
                      "code": {
                        "string": "\\displaystyle F_{i}(\\lambda\\mathbf{x})=\\lambda F_{i}(\\mathbf{x}),"
                      },
                      "mathLanguage": "latex",
                      "mathml": "redacted"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "Paragraph",
                      "content": [
                        {
                          "type": "Text",
                          "value": {
                            "string": "for any "
                          }
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "MathInline",
                          "code": {
                            "string": "\\lambda&gt;0"
                          },
                          "mathLanguage": "latex",
                          "mathml": "redacted"
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "Text",
                          "value": {
                            "string": " and "
                          }
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "MathInline",
                          "code": {
                            "string": "\\mathbf{x}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N+2}_{\\geq 0}"
                          },
                          "mathLanguage": "latex",
                          "mathml": "redacted"
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "Text",
                          "value": {
                            "string": ", and additionally,"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "MathBlock",
                      "code": {
                        "string": "F_{i}(\\mathbf{q},E,L)\\leq c_{i}L\\quad\\text{for some constant $c_{i}<\\infty$}."
                      },
                      "mathLanguage": "latex",
                      "mathml": "redacted"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ],
              "order": "Unordered"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Condition (a) implies that the production function exhibits sublinear growth in total input usage, capturing inefficiencies that arise at high input levels and leading to diminishing marginal gains. This extends the classical notion of "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Emphasis",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "decreasing returns to scale"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", typically characterized by homogeneity of degree less than one."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Condition (b), in contrast, corresponds to "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Emphasis",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "constant returns to scale"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", where output scales proportionally with all inputs. The additional upper bound relative to labor ensures that labor remains an essential input, preventing it from being completely substituted by other production factors."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "For a general discussion of production functions and the economic interpretation of their properties, we refer to standard microeconomic textbooks such as "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib59",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Varian (1992)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib49",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Mas-Colell et al. (1995)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Claim",
          "claimType": "Theorem",
          "label": "2.2",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "The CES (Constant Elasticity of Substitution) production functions form a broad and widely used class of production technologies. In our framework, the CES production function takes the form"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "MathBlock",
              "code": {
                "string": "F_{i}(\\mathbf{q}_{i},E_{i},L_{i})=A_{i}\\left(\\sum_{j=1}^{N}\\alpha_{ij}q_{ij}^{%\n-\\rho_{i}}+\\alpha_{iE}E_{i}^{-\\rho_{i}}+\\alpha_{iL}L_{i}^{-\\rho_{i}}\\right)^{-%\n\\frac{k_{i}}{\\rho_{i}}},\\quad\\rho_{i}>0,\\;k_{i}\\in(0,1],"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "where "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "A_{i}\\geq 0"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " denotes the total factor productivity, and the share parameters "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "\\alpha_{ij}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": ", "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "\\alpha_{iE}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": ", and "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "\\alpha_{iL}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " satisfy"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "MathBlock",
              "code": {
                "string": "\\sum_{j=1}^{N}\\alpha_{ij}+\\alpha_{iE}+\\alpha_{iL}=1."
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "The substitution parameter "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "\\rho_{i}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " determines the elasticity of substitution via"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "MathBlock",
              "code": {
                "string": "ES_{i}=\\frac{1}{1+\\rho_{i}}."
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "The parameter "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "k_{i}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " governs the degree of homogeneity: for "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "k_{i}=1"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": ", the function is linearly homogeneous; for "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "k_{i}&lt;1"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": ", it exhibits sublinear growth."
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "This class satisfies Assumption "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "Link",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": "2.1"
                      }
                    }
                  ],
                  "target": "S2.Thmtheorem1",
                  "title": "Assumption 2.1 (Production function). ‣ 2.1. Production functions ‣ 2. Firm-level profit maximization with carbon pricing ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": ": condition (a) holds for "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "k_{i}&lt;1"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": ", and condition (b) for "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "k_{i}=1"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": ", with "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "c_{i}=\\alpha_{iL}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " ensuring a linear bound in labor. See "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "CitationGroup",
                  "items": [
                    {
                      "type": "Citation",
                      "target": "bib.bib57",
                      "citationMode": "Narrative",
                      "content": [
                        {
                          "type": "Text",
                          "value": {
                            "string": "Uzawa (, 1962"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "Citation",
                      "target": "bib.bib10",
                      "citationMode": "Narrative",
                      "content": [
                        {
                          "type": "Text",
                          "value": {
                            "string": "), Arrow et al. (, 1961"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " for further details."
                  }
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Section",
      "sectionType": "Main",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Heading",
          "label": "2.2.",
