          ],
          "target": "S3",
          "title": "3. Price formation and competitive equilibrium in the static setting ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": " to a dynamic market model over the time interval "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "MathInline",
          "code": {
            "string": "[0,T]"
          },
          "mathLanguage": "latex",
          "mathml": "redacted"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ". The economy consists of "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "MathInline",
          "code": {
            "string": "N"
          },
          "mathLanguage": "latex",
          "mathml": "redacted"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": " sectors, each comprising a continuum of firms that may default at uncertain future times. This formulation, which models an economy with multiple sectors and infinitely many firms per sector, has been explored in the context of portfolio optimization, e.g., in "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Citation",
          "target": "bib.bib20",
          "citationMode": "Narrative",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Borkar and Suresh Kumar (2010)"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ". As in that work and many others applying mean-field game (MFG) theory, we do not analyze the convergence from a finite-agent system to the mean-field limit, but instead work directly with the limiting model."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "We consider an endogenous default framework in which each individual agent in each sector optimally selects its production inputs and the timing of market exit to maximize expected profits over "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "MathInline",
          "code": {
            "string": "[0,T]"
          },
          "mathLanguage": "latex",
          "mathml": "redacted"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "To streamline the equilibrium analysis, we adopt the linear programming approach introduced in "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Citation",
          "target": "bib.bib23",
          "citationMode": "Narrative",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Bouveret et al. (2020)"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": " and "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Citation",
          "target": "bib.bib31",
          "citationMode": "Narrative",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Dumitrescu et al. (2021)"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ", which reformulates the firms’ optimal stopping problem as an equivalent linear program. The central objects of interest are the distributions of states (labor costs) for non-defaulted firms in each sector, as well as the joint distributions of exit times and labor cost trajectories —referred to as exit measures."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "A linear programming MFG Nash equilibrium is defined as a configuration of prices, state distribution flows, and exit measures that jointly satisfy a mean-field version of the market-clearing condition ("
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Link",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "8"
              }
            }
          ],
          "target": "S3.E8",
          "title": "In 3. Price formation and competitive equilibrium in the static setting ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ") and the generic agent’s profit-maximization problem in each sector. The section concludes by proving the existence of such an equilibrium and the uniqueness of the associated price system."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
