        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Using the definition of the maximized instantaneous profit ("
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Link",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "20"
                  }
                }
              ],
              "target": "S4.E20",
              "title": "In 4.1. The optimal default problem of the generic firm ‣ 4. Mean-field game approach to a dynamic market model with defaults ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "), this problem can be equivalently rewritten as:"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "MathBlock",
          "code": {
            "string": "v_{i}(\\mathbf{P},P_{E},x)\\coloneqq\\max_{\\tau_{i}\\in{\\mathcal{T}}([0,T])}%\n\\mathbb{E}_{x}\\left[\\int_{0}^{\\tau_{i}}e^{-rt}\\left\\{\\overline{\\Pi}_{i}(%\n\\mathbf{P}(t),P_{E}(t),X^{i}_{t})-\\kappa_{i}\\right\\}dt-K_{i}e^{-(r+\\gamma_{i})%\n\\tau_{i}}\\right]."
          },
          "mathLanguage": "latex",
          "mathml": "redacted"
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "The value function "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "v_{i}(\\mathbf{P},P_{E},x)"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " represents the equity value of firm "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "i"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", net of the expected discounted liquidation cost incurred at the time of exit. In problems with endogenous default, the optimal default policy typically takes the form of a threshold strategy (see for example "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib44",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Leland and Toft (1996)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ","
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib15",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Bélanger et al. (2004)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib56",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Schmidt and Novikov (2008)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib37",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Frey and Schmidt (2009)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " among many others). That is, the firm exits the industry and liquidates its assets immediately once the labor shock process "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "(X^{i}_{t})_{t\\geq 0}"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " crosses an endogenously determined upper barrier."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "However, in optimal stopping mean-field games, it has been observed "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib18",
              "citationMode": "Parenthetical",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Bertucci, 2018"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " that an equilibrium with pure (threshold-type) stopping times does not always exist. To capture all equilibria, it is necessary to consider a broader class of strategies, namely randomized stopping times. This implies that, at equilibrium, agents may exit at random times within the interval between the minimal optimal stopping time "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "\\tau_{-}"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and the maximal optimal stopping time "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "\\tau_{+}"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", rather than exiting precisely at the first hitting time of a threshold. As a result, a characterization of equilibrium solely in terms of stopping times or default thresholds is not always feasible, and alternative methods have been developed."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "In particular, the linear programming approach introduced by "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib23",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Bouveret et al. (2020)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " circumvents the need to solve individual optimization problems by focusing directly on the evolution of population distributions. This avoids the technical challenges posed by randomized stopping strategies."
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Section",
      "sectionType": "Main",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Heading",
          "label": "4.2.",
          "level": 2,
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Linear programming formulation"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Within the linear programming framework, we reformulate the optimal stopping problem ("
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Link",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "21"
                  }
                }
              ],
              "target": "S4.E21",
              "title": "In 4.1. The optimal default problem of the generic firm ‣ 4. Mean-field game approach to a dynamic market model with defaults ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ") as a linear program over a suitable space of measures. We begin by recalling the following definition from "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Citation",
              "target": "bib.bib23",
              "citationMode": "Narrative",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Bouveret et al. (2020)"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", suitably adapted to our setting."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Claim",
          "claimType": "Theorem",
          "label": "4.4",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "Let "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "p\\geq 1"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " and "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "{\\mathcal{O}}\\subseteq\\mathbb{R}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": ". We define "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "{\\mathcal{V}}_{p}(\\overline{{\\mathcal{O}}})"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " as the space of flows "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "m=(m_{t}(\\cdot))_{t\\in[0,T]}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": " of bounded measures on "
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "MathInline",
                  "code": {
                    "string": "\\overline{{\\mathcal{O}}}"
                  },
                  "mathLanguage": "latex",
                  "mathml": "redacted"
                },
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": ", satisfying the following properties:"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
