          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "Numerical illustration"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "In this section, we present numerical simulations based on CES production functions, CIR dynamics for labor cost processes, and power-type functional forms for demand and labor cost. We consider two stylized models."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "We first analyze a single-sector economy consisting solely of a brown sector, which employs labor and emissions as inputs with equal CES share parameters. This setting allows us to study the effects of a carbon price on (i) capacity evolution, (ii) substitution dynamics — specifically, how emissions are replaced by labor in output production — and (iii) carbon cost pass-through, i.e., the extent to which the carbon price is reflected in final prices passed on to consumers (see "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Citation",
          "target": "bib.bib53",
          "citationMode": "Narrative",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Neuhoff and Ritz (2019)"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ")."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "We then turn to a multi-sector economy composed of three sectors: Brown, Green, and Manufacturing. In this case, the CES input share parameters are set to reflect an input-output structure where Manufacturing requires both Brown and Green goods as inputs, and both Brown and Green sectors consume a fraction of Manufacturing output in their production processes. This setup enables us to study the propagation of carbon pricing through the value chain."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "To isolate the effects of substitution and propagation, we fix the parameters of the CIR labor cost process uniformly across all sectors (see Remark "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Link",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "4.2"
              }
            }
          ],
          "target": "S4.Thmtheorem2",
          "title": "Remark 4.2. ‣ 4.1. The optimal default problem of the generic firm ‣ 4. Mean-field game approach to a dynamic market model with defaults ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "), setting "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "MathInline",
          "code": {
            "string": "\\alpha=0.1"
          },
          "mathLanguage": "latex",
          "mathml": "redacted"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ", "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "MathInline",
          "code": {
            "string": "\\theta=22.5"
          },
          "mathLanguage": "latex",
          "mathml": "redacted"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ", and "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "MathInline",
          "code": {
            "string": "\\sigma=8"
          },
          "mathLanguage": "latex",
          "mathml": "redacted"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "We further assume zero liquidation cost at default, allowing us to focus on sector capacities, as well as the densities of the killed labor cost processes."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "The linear MFG Nash equilibrium is computed using the fictitious play algorithm proposed by "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Citation",
          "target": "bib.bib8",
          "citationMode": "Narrative",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Aïd et al. (2021)"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": " and "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Citation",
          "target": "bib.bib32",
          "citationMode": "Narrative",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Dumitrescu et al. (2023)"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ", combined with explicit expressions for optimal input choices derived in Propositions "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Link",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "4.3"
              }
            }
          ],
          "target": "S4.Thmtheorem3",
          "title": "Proposition 4.3. ‣ 4.1. The optimal default problem of the generic firm ‣ 4. Mean-field game approach to a dynamic market model with defaults ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": " and "
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Link",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "2.8"
              }
            }
          ],
          "target": "S2.Thmtheorem8",
          "title": "Proposition 2.8 (Explicit expression under CES technology). ‣ 2.2. Firm’s profit maximization problem ‣ 2. Firm-level profit maximization with carbon pricing ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": ". For each best response in Problem ("
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Link",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "23"
              }
            }
          ],
          "target": "S4.E23",
          "title": "In 4.2. Linear programming formulation ‣ 4. Mean-field game approach to a dynamic market model with defaults ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
        },
        {
          "type": "Text",
          "value": {
            "string": "), we discretize the Fokker-Planck inequality using an implicit scheme, and evaluate the optimization functional over discretized measures. The resulting optimization problem is solved using the Gurobi library ("
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Link",
          "content": [
            {
