      "sectionType": "Main",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "Heading",
          "label": "5.2.",
          "level": 2,
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Example 2: Substitution in a multi-sector economy"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "In the three-sector economy, we consider the following input-output structure:"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "List",
          "items": [
            {
              "type": "ListItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Paragraph",
                  "content": []
                },
                {
                  "type": "Paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": "The Brown sector uses 0.5 units of emissions, 0.4 units of labor, and 0.1 units of Manufacturing output, with a high substitution parameter "
                      }
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "MathInline",
                      "code": {
                        "string": "\\rho_{B}=1.5"
                      },
                      "mathLanguage": "latex",
                      "mathml": "redacted"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": ", reflecting rigid fossil-based technologies."
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "ListItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Paragraph",
                  "content": []
                },
                {
                  "type": "Paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": "The Green sector uses 0.01 units of emissions, 0.89 units of labor, and 0.1 units of Manufacturing output, with a moderately high substitution parameter "
                      }
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "MathInline",
                      "code": {
                        "string": "\\rho_{G}=0.7"
                      },
                      "mathLanguage": "latex",
                      "mathml": "redacted"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": "."
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "ListItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Paragraph",
                  "content": []
                },
                {
                  "type": "Paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": "The Manufacturing sector uses 0.35 units of Brown output, 0.35 units of Green output, 0.05 units of emissions, and 0.25 units of labor, with a low substitution parameter "
                      }
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "MathInline",
                      "code": {
                        "string": "\\rho_{M}=0.1"
                      },
                      "mathLanguage": "latex",
                      "mathml": "redacted"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "Text",
                      "value": {
                        "string": ", allowing substantial input flexibility."
                      }
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "order": "Unordered"
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "We also examine the impact of carbon pricing on final demand across sectors. Each sector faces a power demand function as in Example "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Link",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "3.2"
                  }
                }
              ],
              "target": "S3.Thmtheorem2",
              "title": "Example 3.2 (Power demand functions). ‣ 3. Price formation and competitive equilibrium in the static setting ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": ", with no exogenous supply. We set "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "a_{B}=100"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "\\epsilon_{B}=2"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " for the Brown sector, modeling high initial demand for fossil-based technologies and strong sensitivity to price increases. This structure captures the idea that Brown goods are initially dominant but highly exposed to carbon pricing."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "For the Green and Manufacturing sectors, we set "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "\\epsilon_{G}=\\epsilon_{M}=0.5"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " to reflect inelastic demand: for Green, due to transition policies such as subsidies, and for Manufacturing, due to its central role in the value chain. The scale parameters are set to "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "a_{G}=1"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " for Green, reflecting a small initial demand, and "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "MathInline",
              "code": {
                "string": "a_{M}=10"
              },
              "mathLanguage": "latex",
              "mathml": "redacted"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " for Manufacturing, indicating intermediate baseline demand."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "We test the model under a more stringent regulatory scenario, with the carbon price rising from $1 to $200 over a ten-year window, from 2025 to 2035."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Figure "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Link",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "3"
                  }
                }
              ],
              "target": "S5.F3",
              "title": "Figure 3 ‣ 5.2. Example 2: Substitution in a multi-sector economy ‣ 5. Numerical illustration ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " shows the evolution of carbon emissions and labor across the three sectors. Emissions drop sharply in all sectors following the carbon price shock, approaching zero in the Green and Manufacturing sectors. In contrast, emissions in the Brown sector remain strictly positive, reflecting its low elasticity of substitution, which limits the ability to fully decarbonize. Labor in the Brown sector also declines, though less than emissions, indicating that, even under technological rigidity, a substitution effect remains observable, with firms replacing costly emissions with labor to the extent permitted by the production function."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "In contrast, both the Green and Manufacturing sectors experience a reallocation of employment rather than a contraction. Their higher substitution elasticities enable them to offset reduced emissions by increasing labor input, thus sustaining production under the carbon constraint. This highlights how decarbonization can shift labor across sectors rather than destroy it, depending on the flexibility of production technologies."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "Figure "
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Link",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "Text",
                  "value": {
                    "string": "4"
                  }
                }
              ],
              "target": "S5.F4",
              "title": "Figure 4 ‣ 5.2. Example 2: Substitution in a multi-sector economy ‣ 5. Numerical illustration ‣ Propagation of carbon price shocks through the value chain: the mean-field game of defaults"
            },
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": " displays the evolution of sectoral production (left panel) and final demand (right panel). All sectors experience a decline in output, though to varying degrees. The Brown sector sees a substantial drop, as it reduces both emissions and labor with limited substitution flexibility. The Green sector experiences only a mild contraction: it successfully replaces emissions with labor, though its dependence on Manufacturing inputs limits a full offset. Manufacturing output declines to a level between that of the Green and Brown sectors, as it partially compensates for the reduction in Brown inputs by increasing reliance on Green goods and labor."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "Text",
              "value": {
                "string": "A similar pattern appears in final demand: the Brown sector experiences a near-complete collapse as its highly elastic consumers curtail purchases, whereas demand for Green goods remains almost unchanged and ultimately exceeds that of the Brown sector."
              }
            }
